{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\deff0\deflang1033{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
{\colortbl ;\red0\green0\blue0;}
{\*\generator Msftedit 5.41.15.1515;}\viewkind4\uc1\pard\cf1\b\f0\fs20 In this task, the Index is hard-coded. It will always open by being sorted by Last Name.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\deff0\deflang1033{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
{\colortbl ;\red0\green0\blue0;\red255\green0\blue128;}
{\*\generator Msftedit 5.41.15.1515;}\viewkind4\uc1\pard\cf1\b\f0\fs20 In this task, the choice of Index is passed in as a parameter.\par
\par
The Index itself is a numeric, and not a value that can be known by the user easily. So a \cf2 Case()\cf1  statement is used to translate between the Combo box value and the actual Index that is use.\par
\par
Also, the \cf2 ''Index\cf1  literal is used so that if the Index value changes in the future, the program does not need to be updated.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\deff0\deflang1033{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
{\colortbl ;\red0\green0\blue0;\red255\green0\blue128;}
{\*\generator Msftedit 5.41.15.1515;}\viewkind4\uc1\pard\cf1\b\f0\fs20 When the desired Index does not exist, data can be automatically sorted by Magic by specifying a sort order under \cf2 Task->Sort\cf1 .\par
\par
In this example, the data is sorted by First name then Last name.\par
}
